{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775907189655,"sessionID":"ses_283af0829ffeKBpaLvjWQ0hTo4","part":{"id":"prt_d7c51335c001rOoFibtJczu6Ob","messageID":"msg_d7c511837001MR5Ol7wct7gUsq","sessionID":"ses_283af0829ffeKBpaLvjWQ0hTo4","type":"tool","tool":"bash","callID":"toolu_tool-c135094e8c80452681fb8403d875e7f7","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"command":"ls -la docs/docs/","description":"List docs/docs directory"},"output":"total 32\ndrwxr-xr-x 8 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:24 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 8 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:22 ..\ndrwxr-xr-x 4 root root 4096 Apr 11 18:54 api\ndrwxr-xr-x 4 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:26 architecture\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Apr 11 18:54 changelog\ndrwxr-xr-x 3 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:24 deployment\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:24 examples\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Apr 11 18:59 getting-started\n","metadata":{"output":"total 32\ndrwxr-xr-x 8 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:24 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 8 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:22 ..\ndrwxr-xr-x 4 root root 4096 Apr 11 18:54 api\ndrwxr-xr-x 4 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:26 architecture\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Apr 11 18:54 changelog\ndrwxr-xr-x 3 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:24 deployment\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Apr 11 19:24 examples\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Apr 11 18:59 getting-started\n","exit":0,"description":"List docs/docs directory","truncated":false},"title":"List docs/docs directory","time":{"start":1775907189628,"end":1775907189654}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775907189687,"sessionID":"ses_283af0829ffeKBpaLvjWQ0hTo4","part":{"id":"prt_d7c513170001lWBlL6j3u0URzz","messageID":"msg_d7c511837001MR5Ol7wct7gUsq","sessionID":"ses_283af0829ffeKBpaLvjWQ0hTo4","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_tool-de0fd31543ff4a1794ee83212c7a702b","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/docs/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-glm-5_20260410T163124Z/docs/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Delta Spec: Architecture Design Documentation & API Documentation\n2: \n3: **AR:** AR-043 — 架构设计文档与 API 文档  \n4: **Module:** docs  \n5: **Language:** Markdown  \n6: **Size:** M\n7: \n8: ---\n9: \n10: ## OpenSpec Format\n11: \n12: Each requirement follows GIVEN/WHEN/THEN structure for acceptance scenarios.\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## REQ-001: System Architecture Overview Documentation\n17: \n18: ### Description\n19: \n20: Provide comprehensive system architecture documentation explaining AgentCube's core components, deployment topology, and interaction flows.\n21: \n22: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n23: \n24: #### Scenario: Architecture overview page exists\n25: - **GIVEN** the Docusaurus documentation site at `docs/docs/architecture/`\n26: - **WHEN** a user navigates to the architecture overview page\n27: - **THEN** a file `overview.md` exists in the architecture directory\n28: - **AND** the page renders successfully in Docusaurus\n29: - **AND** the content includes high-level system purpose and tech stack\n30: \n31: #### Scenario: Architecture includes component diagram\n32: - **GIVEN** the architecture overview documentation\n33: - **WHEN** the document is viewed\n34: - **THEN** an ASCII or Mermaid diagram shows the system topology:\n35:   - Router ↔ Redis/Valkey ↔ WorkloadManager ↔ K8s API\n36:   - Sandbox Pods with PicoD daemon\n37:   - Agentd idle cleanup controller\n38: - **AND** the diagram uses clear component labels and arrows showing data flow\n39: \n40: #### Scenario: Tech stack table is documented\n41: - **GIVEN** the architecture overview page\n42: - **WHEN** the tech stack section is viewed\n43: - **THEN** a table lists each technology layer:\n44:   - Go 1.24 for server components\n45:   - Python ≥3.10 for CLI/SDK\n46:   - Gin (Go HTTP framework)\n47:   - Kubernetes CRDs (`runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh/v1alpha1`)\n48:   - Redis/Valkey for session storage\n49:   - JWT RS256 for authentication\n50: - **AND** each technology has a purpose column explaining its role\n51: \n52: #### Scenario: Deployment topology is explained\n53: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n54: - **WHEN** the deployment topology section is viewed\n55: - **THEN** the document describes three deployment patterns:\n56:   1. Router as Deployment (Pod :8080)\n57:   2. WorkloadManager as Deployment with Redis connection\n58:   3. Sandbox Pods with optional PicoD sidecar\n59: - **AND** each deployment pattern has resource requirements and scaling notes\n60: \n61: ---\n62: \n63: ## REQ-002: Component Architecture Documentation\n64: \n65: ### Description\n66: \n67: Document each major system component with detailed architecture, responsibilities, and integration points.\n68: \n69: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n70: \n71: #### Scenario: Router component architecture page exists\n72: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation directory\n73: - **WHEN** a user views the Router component page (`router.md`)\n74: - **THEN** the document explains Router's role:\n75:   - Session routing and reverse proxy\n76:   - JWT token validation\n77:   - Traffic routing to sandbox pods\n78: - **AND** the page includes:\n79:   - Request flow diagram\n80:   - Session management logic description\n81:   - Supported endpoints table (`/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path`)\n82: \n83: #### Scenario: WorkloadManager component documentation\n84: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n85: - **WHEN** a user views the WorkloadManager component page (`workloadmanager.md`)\n86: - **THEN** the document describes:\n87:   - Sandbox lifecycle management (create, delete, garbage collection)\n88:   - Kubernetes API interactions (CRDs, Pods, Secrets)\n89:   - Health check and metrics endpoints\n90: - **AND** includes endpoint documentation:\n91:   - `/sandboxes` POST (create sandbox)\n92:   - `/sandboxes/:id` GET/DELETE\n93:   - `/health/live` and `/health/ready`\n94: \n95: #### Scenario: PicoD daemon architecture documented\n96: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation directory\n97: - **WHEN** a user views the PicoD component page (`picod.md`)\n98: - **THEN** the document explains:\n99:   - Local code execution daemon running as sidecar\n100:   - Workspace isolation and sanitization\n101:   - File operations (upload, download, list)\n102:   - Code execution timeout management\n103: - **AND** provides endpoint details:\n104:   - `/api/execute` POST for code execution\n105:   - `/api/files` POST/GET for file operations\n106: \n107: #### Scenario: Agentd idle cleanup controller documented\n108: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n109: - **WHEN** the Agentd component page (`agentd.md`) is viewed\n110: - **THEN** the document explains:\n111:   - Kubernetes controller-runtime architecture\n112:   - Idle threshold detection logic\n113:   - Leader election for singleton controller\n114:   - Cleanup workflow steps\n115: - **AND** includes configuration parameters documentation:\n116:   - `--idle-threshold` (default 30m)\n117:   - `--check-interval` (default 5m)\n118:   - `--leader-election` flag\n119: \n120: ---\n121: \n122: ## REQ-003: Data Flow Documentation\n123: \n124: ### Description\n125: \n126: Document how data flows through the system for key operations (sandbox creation, code execution, session routing).\n127: \n128: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n129: \n130: #### Scenario: Sandbox creation flow documented\n131: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n132: - **WHEN** the data flow section is viewed\n133: - **THEN** a step-by-step flow diagram exists for sandbox creation:\n134:   1. SDK → Router (JWT authenticated request)\n135:   2. Router → WorkloadManager (sandbox creation request)\n136:   3. WorkloadManager → Kubernetes API (create Pod, Secret, CRDs)\n137:   4. WorkloadManager → Router (return sandbox endpoint)\n138:   5. Router → SDK (session response with sandbox URL)\n139: - **AND** each step includes timeout and retry behavior notes\n140: \n141: #### Scenario: Code execution flow documented\n142: - **GIVEN** the data flow documentation\n143: - **WHEN** the code execution flow page is viewed\n144: - **THEN** the document shows the execution flow:\n145:   1. Client sends code via Router to sandbox pod\n146:   2. Router validates JWT and routes to correct sandbox\n147:   3. PicoD receives request in sandbox pod\n148:   4. PicoD executes code with workspace isolation\n149:   5. Response returns through Router to client\n150: - **AND** includes error handling scenarios:\n151:   - Timeout during execution\n152:   - Sandbox pod not ready\n153:   - Invalid authentication token\n154: \n155: #### Scenario: Session routing flow documented\n156: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n157: - **WHEN** the session routing flow section is viewed\n158: - **THEN** the document explains how Router maintains session state:\n159:   - Redis/Valkey stores session-to-sandbox mappings\n160:   - Session key structure documented (`session:<id>`)\n161:   - Session TTL and cleanup logic\n162: - **AND** includes session lifecycle states:\n163:   - Created, Active, Expired, Terminated\n164: \n165: ---\n166: \n167: ## REQ-004: Python SDK API Documentation\n168: \n169: ### Description\n170: \n171: Provide complete API documentation for the Python SDK (`agentcube-sdk`) with code examples and type signatures.\n172: \n173: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n174: \n175: #### Scenario: Python SDK overview page exists\n176: - **GIVEN** the API documentation directory at `docs/docs/api/sdk-python/`\n177: - **WHEN** a user navigates to the SDK overview (`overview.md`)\n178: - **THEN** the page includes:\n179:   - Installation instructions (`pip install agentcube-sdk`)\n180:   - Quick start code example\n181:   - SDK architecture diagram showing Control Plane vs Data Plane\n182:   - Version compatibility table\n183: \n184: #### Scenario: CodeInterpreterClient API documented\n185: - **GIVEN** the Python SDK API documentation\n186: - **WHEN** a user views the CodeInterpreterClient API page (`code-interpreter-client.md`)\n187: - **THEN** the document provides complete API reference:\n188:   - Class initialization parameters (`router_url`, `workload_manager_url`, `jwt_token`)\n189:   - `execute_code(language, code, timeout)` method signature and return type\n190:   - `execute_command(command)` method signature\n191:   - `upload_file(path, content)` method\n192:   - `download_file(path)` method\n193:   - `list_files()` method\n194:   - `create_session()` and `stop_session()` methods\n195: - **AND** each method includes:\n196:   - Type annotations (Python 3.10+)\n197:   - Parameter descriptions\n198:   - Return value documentation\n199:   - Exception types that can be raised\n200:   - Code example snippet\n201: \n202: #### Scenario: AgentRuntimeClient API documented\n203: - **GIVEN** the Python SDK API documentation\n204: - **WHEN** the AgentRuntimeClient API page (`agent-runtime-client.md`) is viewed\n205: - **THEN** the document includes:\n206:   - Client initialization parameters\n207:   - `invoke_agent(agent_name, input_data)` method\n208:   - Session management for agent invocations\n209:   - Response format documentation\n210: - **AND** provides examples for:\n211:   - Basic agent invocation\n212:   - Session reuse with multiple invocations\n213:   - Error handling patterns\n214: \n215: #### Scenario: Exception hierarchy documented\n216: - **GIVEN** the Python SDK API documentation\n217: - **WHEN** a user views the exceptions page (`exceptions.md`)\n218: - **THEN** the document lists all exception types:\n219:   - `AgentCubeError` (base exception)\n220:   - `CommandExecutionError` (code/command failures)\n221:   - `SessionError` (session lifecycle errors)\n222:   - `DataPlaneError` (PicoD communication errors)\n223:   - `AuthenticationError` (JWT validation failures)\n224: - **AND** each exception includes:\n225:   - Inheritance hierarchy\n226:   - Exception attributes (e.g., `exit_code`, `stderr` for CommandExecutionError)\n227:   - Example code showing how to catch and handle the exception\n228: \n229: #### Scenario: Session management patterns documented\n230: - **GIVEN** the Python SDK documentation\n231: - **WHEN** the session management page (`sessions.md`) is viewed\n232: - **THEN** the document explains:\n233:   - Session creation and configuration options\n234:   - Session reuse with context manager pattern\n235:   - Explicit session termination\n236:   - Session timeout behavior\n237: - **AND** provides code examples:\n238:   ```python\n239:   # Context manager pattern\n240:   with CodeInterpreterClient(...) as client:\n241:       client.execute_code(\"python\", \"print('hello')\")\n242:   # Explicit session management\n243:   client = CodeInterpreterClient(...)\n244:   session = client.create_session()\n245:   client.execute_code(\"python\", \"code\", session_id=session.id)\n246:   client.stop_session(session.id)\n247:   ```\n248: \n249: ---\n250: \n251: ## REQ-005: Go Client API Documentation\n252: \n253: ### Description\n254: \n255: Provide complete API documentation for the Go client (`client-go`) with Kubernetes-native patterns and type signatures.\n256: \n257: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n258: \n259: #### Scenario: Go client overview page exists\n260: - **GIVEN** the API documentation directory at `docs/docs/api/client-go/`\n261: - **WHEN** a user navigates to the Go client overview (`overview.md`)\n262: - **THEN** the page includes:\n263:   - Installation via Go module (`github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go`)\n264:   - Kubernetes client-go integration explanation\n265:   - CRD types (`AgentRuntime`, `CodeInterpreter`)\n266:   - Version compatibility with Kubernetes versions\n267: \n268: #### Scenario: Clientset construction documented\n269: - **GIVEN** the Go client API documentation\n270: - **WHEN** a user views the Clientset documentation (`clientset.md`)\n271: - **THEN** the document provides:\n272:   - `NewForConfig(config *rest.Config)` function signature\n273:   - `NewForConfigOrDie(config)` panic variant\n274:   - Clientset interface methods (`RuntimeV1alpha1()`, `Discovery()`)\n275: - **AND** includes code example:\n276:   ```go\n277:   config, err := clientcmd.BuildConfigFromFlags(\"\", kubeconfigPath)\n278:   clientset, err := clientset.NewForConfig(config)\n279:   runtimeClient := clientset.RuntimeV1alpha1().AgentRuntimes(namespace)\n280:   ```\n281: \n282: #### Scenario: AgentRuntime CRUD operations documented\n283: - **GIVEN** the Go client API documentation\n284: - **WHEN** the AgentRuntime operations page (`agent-runtime-crud.md`) is viewed\n285: - **THEN** the document lists all CRUD methods:\n286:   - `Create(ctx, agentRuntime, metav1.CreateOptions{})`\n287:   - `Get(ctx, name, metav1.GetOptions{})`\n288:   - `List(ctx, metav1.ListOptions{})`\n289:   - `Update(ctx, agentRuntime, metav1.UpdateOptions{})`\n290:   - `UpdateStatus(ctx, agentRuntime, metav1.UpdateOptions{})`\n291:   - `Delete(ctx, name, metav1.DeleteOptions{})`\n292:   - `DeleteCollection(ctx, metav1.DeleteOptions{}, metav1.ListOptions{})`\n293:   - `Patch(ctx, name, patchType, patch, metav1.PatchOptions{})`\n294:   - `Watch(ctx, metav1.ListOptions{})`\n295: - **AND** each method includes:\n296:   - Go type signatures\n297:   - Parameter descriptions\n298:   - Return types and errors\n299:   - Code example\n300: \n301: #### Scenario: CodeInterpreter CRUD operations documented\n302: - **GIVEN** the Go client API documentation\n303: - **WHEN** the CodeInterpreter operations page (`code-interpreter-crud.md`) is viewed\n304: - **THEN** the document mirrors AgentRuntime CRUD documentation structure\n305: - **AND** includes examples for all CRUD operations on CodeInterpreter resources\n306: \n307: #### Scenario: Informer and Lister patterns documented\n308: - **GIVEN** the Go client API documentation\n309: - **WHEN** the informer documentation page (`informer.md`) is viewed\n310: - **THEN** the document explains:\n311:   - `SharedInformerFactory` construction\n312:   - `Start(stopCh)` and `Shutdown()` methods\n313:   - `WaitForCacheSync(stopCh)` for cache synchronization\n314:   - AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter informers\n315:   - Lister interface usage patterns\n316: - **AND** provides code examples:\n317:   ```go\n318:   factory := externalversions.NewSharedInformerFactory(clientset, 30*time.Second)\n319:   informer := factory.Runtime().V1alpha1().AgentRuntimes()\n320:   stopCh := make(chan struct{})\n321:   factory.Start(stopCh)\n322:   factory.WaitForCacheSync(stopCh)\n323:   lister := informer.Lister()\n324:   ar, err := lister.AgentRuntimes(namespace).Get(name)\n325:   ```\n326: \n327: #### Scenario: Fake clientset for testing documented\n328: - **GIVEN** the Go client API documentation\n329: - **WHEN** the testing page (`testing.md`) is viewed\n330: - **THEN** the document explains:\n331:   - `NewSimpleClientset()` for unit testing\n332:   - Adding reactors for custom behavior\n333:   - Object tracking and retrieval\n334:   - Watch simulation in tests\n335: - **AND** includes test example code snippet\n336: \n337: ---\n338: \n339: ## REQ-006: CRD Schema Documentation\n340: \n341: ### Description\n342: \n343: Document the Kubernetes Custom Resource Definition schemas for AgentRuntime and CodeInterpreter.\n344: \n345: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n346: \n347: #### Scenario: AgentRuntime CRD schema documented\n348: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n349: - **WHEN** a user views the CRD schema page (`crd-agent-runtime.md`)\n350: - **THEN** the document includes:\n351:   - Full YAML schema example\n352:   - Spec fields documentation:\n353:     - `replicas` (integer, default 1)\n354:     - `image` (string, required)\n355:     - `resources` (ResourceRequirements)\n356:     - `env` (array of EnvVar)\n357:     - `volumeMounts` (array)\n358:   - Status fields documentation:\n359:     - `phase` (Running, Pending, Failed)\n360:     - `conditions` (array of Condition)\n361:     - `podName` (string)\n362: - **AND** includes validation rules and default values\n363: \n364: #### Scenario: CodeInterpreter CRD schema documented\n365: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n366: - **WHEN** a user views the CodeInterpreter CRD schema (`crd-code-interpreter.md`)\n367: - **THEN** the document provides:\n368:   - Full YAML schema example\n369:   - Spec fields:\n370:     - `language` (python, javascript, typescript)\n371:     - `timeout` (duration string)\n372:     - `workspaceSize` (resource quantity)\n373:   - Status fields:\n374:     - `sessionID` (string)\n375:     - `podIP` (string)\n376:     - `lastExecutionTime` (timestamp)\n377: - **AND** includes example YAML manifest\n378: \n379: #### Scenario: CRD API version documented\n380: - **GIVEN** the CRD documentation\n381: - **WHEN** the API version section is viewed\n382: - **THEN** the document states the API group and version:\n383:   - API group: `runtime.agentcube.volcano.sh`\n384:   - Version: `v1alpha1`\n385: - **AND** explains version stability status and future versioning plans\n386: \n387: ---\n388: \n389: ## REQ-007: Configuration Documentation\n390: \n391: ### Description\n392: \n393: Document configuration options for each binary component with command-line flags and environment variables.\n394: \n395: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n396: \n397: #### Scenario: Router configuration documented\n398: - **GIVEN** the architecture documentation\n399: - **WHEN** the Router configuration page (`router-config.md`) is viewed\n400: - **THEN** the document lists all configuration options:\n401:   - `--port` (default :8080)\n402:   - `--store-addr` (Redis address)\n403:   - `--store-type` (redis/valkey)\n404:   - `--max-concurrent` (default 1000)\n405:   - `--enable-tls` and `--tls-cert/--tls-key`\n406:   - Environment variable overrides (`PORT`, `STORE_ADDR`, `STORE_TYPE`)\n407: - **AND** each option includes:\n408:   - Default value\n409:   - Valid values/ranges\n410:   - Usage description\n411:   - Example command line\n412: \n413: #### Scenario: WorkloadManager configuration documented\n414: - **GIVEN** the configuration documentation\n415: - **WHEN** the WorkloadManager configuration page (`workloadmanager-config.md`) is viewed\n416: - **THEN** the document lists:\n417:   - `--addr` (HTTP server address)\n418:   - `--gc-interval` (garbage collection interval, default 5m)\n419:   - `--kubeconfig` (Kubernetes config path)\n420:   - HTTP timeout configurations (`--read-timeout`, `--write-timeout`)\n421: - **AND** provides example deployment YAML with configuration\n422: \n423: #### Scenario: PicoD configuration documented\n424: - **GIVEN** the configuration documentation\n425: - **WHEN** the PicoD configuration page (`picod-config.md`) is viewed\n426: - **THEN** the document includes:\n427:   - `--port` (default 8080)\n428:   - `--workspace` (workspace directory path)\n429:   - `--auth-enabled` (JWT authentication toggle)\n430:   - `--max-exec-time` (execution timeout, default 30s)\n431:   - `--max-file-size` (file size limit, default 10MB)\n432:   - `--sanitize-root` (path sanitization root)\n433: - **AND** includes security configuration best practices\n434: \n435: #### Scenario: Agentd configuration documented\n436: - **GIVEN** the configuration documentation\n437: - **WHEN** the Agentd configuration page (`agentd-config.md`) is viewed\n438: - **THEN** the document lists:\n439:   - `--idle-threshold` (default 30m)\n440:   - `--check-interval` (default 5m)\n441:   - `--max-concurrent-cleanup` (default 10)\n442:   - `--leader-election` (default true)\n443:   - `--namespace` (watched namespaces)\n444: - **AND** explains leader election configuration\n445: \n446: ---\n447: \n448: ## REQ-008: Deployment Documentation\n449: \n450: ### Description\n451: \n452: Provide deployment guides for installing AgentCube on Kubernetes with Helm charts.\n453: \n454: ### Acceptance Scenarios\n455: \n456: #### Scenario: Helm installation guide documented\n457: - **GIVEN** the deployment documentation directory at `docs/docs/deployment/`\n458: - **WHEN** the Helm installation page (`helm-installation.md`) is viewed\n459: - **THEN** the document provides:\n460:   - Helm chart location\n461:   - Installation command: `helm install agentcube ./manifests/helm/agentcube`\n462:   - Required values configuration:\n463:     - Redis/Valkey connection settings\n464:     - JWT configuration\n465:     - Kubernetes namespace\n466:   - Optional values table\n467: - **AND** includes post-installation verification steps\n468: \n469: #### Scenario: Prerequisites documented\n470: - **GIVEN** the deployment documentation\n471: - **WHEN** the prerequisites page (`prerequisites.md`) is viewed\n472: - **THEN** the document lists:\n473:   - Kubernetes version requirements (≥1.24)\n474:   - Required cluster resources (CPU, memory)\n475:   - Redis/Valkey deployment\n476:   - Helm 3 installation\n477:   - kubectl configuration\n478: - **AND** provides setup commands for each prerequisite\n479: \n480: #### Scenario: Multi-namespace deployment documented\n481: - **GIVEN** the deployment documentation\n482: - **WHEN** the multi-namespace deployment page (`multi-namespace.md`) is viewed\n483: - **THEN** the document explains:\n484:   - Deploying Router and WorkloadManager in separate namespaces\n485:   - Cross-namespace communication configuration\n486:   - RBAC requirements for multi-namespace access\n487: - **AND**